      "can try to find a reference. \n\n**Searching online:**\nAha! This is known as **Morgan's Theorem**. \n\nHere is a proof sketch:\n\nWe can write the quotient as `(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n! (m + n)!)`.\n\nFirst, we will prove that `(m + n)!` divides `(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n!)`.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps it is better to find an explicit expression as a product of binomial coefficients or something else.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can use induction.\n\nBut in Lean, we can use existing lemmas.\n\nBut perhaps the following works:\n\n`(2m)! / (m! (m + n)!) * (2n)! / (n! (m + n)!)` but this doesn't directly help because `(m + n)!` appears twice. \n\nAlternatively, we can note that `(2m)! / (m! m!)` and `(2n)! / (n! n!)` are integers. So `(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n! m! n!)` is an integer.\n\nWe need to show that we can further divide by `(m + n)! / (m! n!)` (which is `(m + n choose n)`).\n\nBut perhaps `(m + n choose n)` divides `(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n! m! n!)`? \n\nThis seems to require that `(m + n choose n)` divides `binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n)`.\n\nBut does it? \n\nFor example, take `m = 1`, `n = 2`:\n`(1 + 2 choose 2) = 3`, `binomial(2, 1) = 2`, `binomial(4, 2) = 6`. `2 * 6 = 12` and `3` divides `12`.\n\nTake `m = 2`, `n = 1`: same. \n\n`m = 2`, `n = 2`: `(4 choose 2) = 6`, `binomial(4,2) = 6`, product is `36`, and `6` divides `36`.\n\nHmm, this seems to hold empirically. \n\nBut is it true in general that `(m + n choose n)` divides `binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n)`?\n\nLet me try to check another case: `m = 1`, `n = 3`.\n\n`(1 + 3 choose 3) = 4`, `binomial(2, 1) = 2`, `binomial(6, 3) = 20`. `2 * 20 = 40`, and `4` divides `40`. \n\nYes.\n\nAnother case: `m = 2`, `n = 3`.\n\n`(5 choose 3) = 10`, `binomial(4, 2) = 6`, `binomial(6, 3) = 20`, `6 * 20 = 120`, `10` divides `120`. \n\nThis suggests that perhaps `(m + n choose n)` divides `binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n)`.\n\nIf we can prove this, then we can deduce that `(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n! (m + n)!)` is an integer because:\n\n`(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n! (m + n)!) = ( (2m)! / (m! m!) ) * ( (2n)! / (n! n!) ) * (m! n!) / (m + n)! = binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n) / binomial(m + n, m)`.\n\nBut if `(m + n choose m)` divides `binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n)`, then `binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n) / binomial(m + n, m)` is an integer, which completes the proof.\n\nBut instead of trying to prove that `(m + n choose n)` divides `binomial(2m, m) * binomial(2n, n)` directly, perhaps we can use another approach.\n\n**Alternative Approach with Factor Multiplicity:**\n\nLet's instead try to show that for every prime `p`, the exponent of `p` in `m! n! (m + n)!` is less than or equal to its exponent in `(2m)! (2n)!`.\n\nWe can use Legendre's formula for the exponent of `p` in `k!`: it is `sum_{i >= 1} floor(k / p^i)`.\n\nThus, for each prime `p`, we need:\n\n`sum_{i >= 1} floor(m / p^i) + sum_{i >= 1} floor(n / p^i) + sum_{i >= 1} floor((m + n) / p^i) <= sum_{i >= 1} floor(2m / p^i) + sum_{i >= 1} floor(2n / p^i)`.\n\nBut for each `i`, we need to check whether `floor(m / p^i) + floor(n / p^i) + floor((m + n) / p^i) <= floor(2m / p^i) + floor(2n / p^i)`.\n\nThis seems tricky. \n\nHowever, perhaps it is easier to use the following: for any non-negative integers `a, b`, we have `floor(a / p^i) + floor(b / p^i) <= floor((a + b) / p^i)`. \n\nBut in our case, if we set `a = m`, `b = n`, we get `floor(m / p^i) + floor(n / p^i) <= floor((m + n)/p^i)",
