      "\\binom{m + n}{m} = \\binom{2m + 2n}{m + n} \\binom{2m + 2n}{2m} / \\binom{m + n}{m}.\n$$\nThis seems complicated. \n\n**Final Approach: Using Multinomial Coefficients**\nNotice that $(2m)! (2n)! / (m! n! (m + n)!)$ can be written as:\n$$\n\\frac{(2m)!}{m! m!} \\cdot \\frac{(2n)!}{n! n!} \\cdot \\frac{m! n! (m + n)!}{(m + n)!} = \\binom{2m}{m} \\binom{2n}{n} \\cdot \\text{something}.\n$$\nThis is not directly helpful, but instead, consider that:\n$$\n\\frac{(2m)! (2n)!}{m! n! (m + n)!} = \\binom{2m}{m} \\binom{2n}{n} \\cdot \\frac{m! n!}{(m + n)!} \\cdot \\frac{(2m)! (2n)!}{(2m)! (2n)!} \n$$\nThis seems too convoluted. \n\n**Alternative Approach: Using Stronger Results**\nPerhaps we can find a stronger result like $(a + b)! (a + c)! (b + c)! \\mid (2a)! (2b)! (2c)!$ for $a, b, c \\geq 0$, which would generalize our problem (set $a = m, b = n, c = 0$). \n\nBut I'm not sure if this is true. \n\n**Going Back to Basics: Direct Proof Using Factorizations**\nInstead, let's think about the exponents of primes in the factorizations. By Legendre's formula, for a prime $p$, the exponent of $p$ in $k!$ is $\\sum_{i=1}^\\infty \\lfloor k / p^i \\rfloor$. \n\nWe need to show that for every prime $p$, the exponent in $m! n! (m + n)!$ is at most that in $(2m)! (2n)!$. \n\nSo, we need to prove that for every prime $p$:\n$$\nv_p(m!) + v_p(n!) + v_p((m + n)!) \\leq v_p((2m)!) + v_p((2n)!).\n$$\nUsing Legendre's formula, this becomes:\n$$\n\\sum_{i=1}^\\infty \\left( \\left\\lfloor \\frac{m}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor + \\left\\lfloor \\frac{n}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor + \\left\\lfloor \\frac{m + n}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor \\right) \\leq \\sum_{i=1}^\\infty \\left( \\left\\lfloor \\frac{2m}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor + \\left\\lfloor \\frac{2n}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor \\right).\n$$\nIt is sufficient to prove that for every $i \\geq 1$:\n$$\n\\left\\lfloor \\frac{m}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor + \\left\\lfloor \\frac{n}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor + \\left\\lfloor \\frac{m + n}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor \\leq \\left\\lfloor \\frac{2m}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor + \\left\\lfloor \\frac{2n}{p^i} \\right\\rfloor.\n$$\n\nBut $\\lfloor m / p^i \\rfloor + \\lfloor n / p^i \\rfloor + \\lfloor (m + n) / p^i \\",
